## 5. Execution order and gate (by scope)

Execution order and dependencies are carried directly by the **execution scope**,
going from coarsest to finest. There is a single organizing axis — the scope — with
two values only:

**1. `FILE`** — global checks done *before* processing the data:
- readability / non-corruption (the file opens and parses);
- non-empty (at least one data row);
- header conformance to the schema (right columns, right order);
- column existence and declared type.

**2. `DATAFRAME`** — everything computed in Polars vectorized pass(es) over the data,
once the structure is validated: cell values (`PER_CELL`), cross-column relations
(`CROSS_COLUMN`), column aggregates (`COLUMN_AGGREGATE`) and cross aggregates
(`CROSS_AGGREGATE`). All these natures compute in the same pass(es) — Polars scans the
column once and applies several stacked checks; distinguishing cell from column for
*execution* would be artificial.

**The gate acts only on structural checks — `FILE` and column existence/type.**

- If a `FILE` blocking check fails (unreadable, empty, non-conformant header), the
  `DATAFRAME` scope is not entered: validating values would be meaningless.
- At the structural column level: **all** column-structure checks run first (to get the
  full picture of columns in error), and *only then* does the gate block the move to
  value checks if a structural column failed. We don't cut off at the first faulty
  column — we want to see all broken columns at once (essential for diagnostics).
- **Below, no gate**: value checks (`PER_CELL`, `CROSS_COLUMN`, aggregates) all run in
  **collect** mode — everything is evaluated, all errors aggregated, nothing cuts off.
  This preserves exhaustiveness and the config-vs-data diagnostic (100% of a column,
  all columns failing…).

Effective order: `FILE` (gate) → column structure (gate) → values on the `DATAFRAME`
(full collection, no gate).

The report indicates `stopped_at` (the structural check that blocked) if applicable. A
`BLOCKING` rule whose errors are all `WAIVED` (exempted columns, cf. 4.4) is treated as
non-blocking.

> **Note.** The cell / cross-column / aggregate distinction is not an execution scope
> but a **rule metadata** (`check_nature`, cf. 4.2). It doesn't change *how* we execute
> (all done in a vectorized pass over the `DATAFRAME`), but it tells the report and
> diagnostic *how to interpret* the result: a per-row verdict (list of faulty rows) or
> an aggregate (column property, global failure rate). Polars provides both in the same
> pass: the per-row boolean expression gives the detail, a `.sum()`/`.all()`/
> `.n_unique()` on that same expression gives the aggregate.

